{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01TQPqUuy4m7jnpKBEYgHXWn","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have a complete picture. Let me create a comprehensive summary with the relevant code sections.\n\n## Summary: Workflow DSL Step Parsing and Config Values\n\nI've examined the parser, domain types, and example workflow. Here's what I found:\n\n### Step Types and Config Structure\n\n**Domain types** (`/workspace/internal/domain/workflow.go`):\n```go\ntype Step struct {\n    Name    string\n    Type    StepType\n    Results []string\n    Config  map[string]string    // All config is stored as strings\n}\n\ntype StepType string\nconst (\n    StepTypeAgent    StepType = \"agent\"      // prompt-based, runs an agent\n    StepTypeScript   StepType = \"script\"     // run shell command\n    StepTypeWorkflow StepType = \"workflow\"   // invoke another workflow\n)\n```\n\n**Known Config Keys** (defined in `/workspace/internal/domain/workflow.go:135-146`):\n- `prompt` — File path or direct string for agent steps (resolved via `file()` function)\n- `run` — Shell command for script steps\n- `max_attempts` — Max retry count (string, converted to int)\n- `timeout` — Execution timeout\n- `agent_command` — Override agent command (e.g., \"claude\")\n- `agent_args` — Override agent arguments\n- `results` — Result names (but stored separately, not in Config)\n- `feedback` — Enable feedback inclusion (\"true\"/\"false\")\n- `workflow_name` — Name of workflow to invoke (for workflow steps)\n- `prompt_step` — Step to use for workflow prompt\n- `container.*` — Container config (any key with prefix allowed)\n\n### How the Parser Sets Config Values\n\n**Parser flow** (`/workspace/internal/dsl/parser.go:139-198`):\n\n1. **Step parsing** (`parseStep()` lines 139-198):\n   - Parses step name and fields into `Config` map\n   - **Type inference** (lines 166-195): Looks at which of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name` is present\n   - Must have exactly one of these three keys\n\n2. **Field parsing** (`parseStepField()` lines 200-248):\n   - Handles regular fields: `key = value` → `Config[\"key\"] = value`\n   - Handles nested blocks: `container { image = \"...\" }` → `Config[\"container.image\"] = ...`\n   - Special case: `results = [...]` stores identifiers in `Step.Results`, NOT in `Config`\n   - String lists stored as comma-separated: `[\"a\", \"b\"]` → `\"a,b\"`\n\n3. **Value parsing** (`parseValue()` lines 298-342):\n   - Handles function calls: `file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")` → stored as string `file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")`\n   - Handles dotted paths: `step.code.output` → stored as literal string `\"step.code.output\"`\n   - Direct strings or identifiers stored as-is\n\n### File Path Storage\n\n**Key insight**: File paths are **not resolved during parsing**—they're stored in their raw form:\n- `prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")` → stored as `Config[\"prompt\"] = 'file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")'`\n- Resolution happens later in `prompt.resolveContent()` (`/workspace/internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go:321-333`)\n\nThe resolver extracts the path from the `file(\"...\")` syntax:\n```go\nfunc resolveContent(value string, workDir string) (string, error) {\n    // Check for file(\"path\") syntax from DSL parser\n    if strings.HasPrefix(value, `file(\"`) && strings.HasSuffix(value, `\")`) {\n        path := value[6 : len(value)-2]  // Extract path from file(\"...\")\n        data, err := os.ReadFile(filepath.Join(workDir, path))\n        if err != nil {\n            return \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"reading file %q: %w\", path, err)\n        }\n        return string(data), nil\n    }\n    return value, nil\n}\n```\n\n### Example Workflow\n\n`.cloche/develop.cloche` shows actual usage:\n```\nstep implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")    # Config[\"prompt\"] = 'file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")'\n    results = [success, fail]                         # Step.Results = [\"success\", \"fail\"]\n}\n\nstep test {\n    run = \"go test ./... 2>&1\"                        # Config[\"run\"] = \"go test ./... 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]                         # Step.Results = [\"success\", \"fail\"]\n}\n\nstep fix {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"2\"                                # Config[\"max_attempts\"] = \"2\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n}\n```\n\n### Runtime Usage\n\nWhen executing:\n1. **Agent steps** (`/workspace/internal/agent/runner.go:110-138`): Check for `step.Config[\"prompt\"]` or `step.Config[\"run\"]`\n2. **Max attempts** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go:70-78`): Read `Config[\"max_attempts\"]` as string, parse to int\n3. **Feedback** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go:300`): Check `step.Config[\"feedback\"] == \"true\"`\n4. **Agent command override** (`/workspace/internal/agent/runner.go:123-128`): Read and parse `step.Config[\"agent_command\"]` and `step.Config[\"agent_args\"]`\n\nAll config values remain strings throughout—conversion happens only where needed (e.g., parsing max_attempts to int, checking feedback equality)."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a3f47e17774230873 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\n<usage>total_tokens: 38376\ntool_uses: 11\nduration_ms: 25540</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"287f3a27-118f-4f7e-b0f1-0e7789c0a986","uuid":"d5db000a-f318-47f8-b688-eea773598fdc","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"I need to understand how steps are parsed in the workflow DSL and what config values they produce. Look at:\n1. internal/dsl/ - the parser, what config keys does it set for steps (prompt, command, script)?\n2. internal/domain/ - the Workflow and Step types\n3. .cloche/develop.cloche - an example workflow file\n\nShow me the relevant code. Be thorough about showing what config keys get set and how file paths are stored.","agentId":"a3f47e17774230873","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Perfect! Now I have a complete picture. Let me create a comprehensive summary with the relevant code sections.\n\n## Summary: Workflow DSL Step Parsing and Config Values\n\nI've examined the parser, domain types, and example workflow. Here's what I found:\n\n### Step Types and Config Structure\n\n**Domain types** (`/workspace/internal/domain/workflow.go`):\n```go\ntype Step struct {\n    Name    string\n    Type    StepType\n    Results []string\n    Config  map[string]string    // All config is stored as strings\n}\n\ntype StepType string\nconst (\n    StepTypeAgent    StepType = \"agent\"      // prompt-based, runs an agent\n    StepTypeScript   StepType = \"script\"     // run shell command\n    StepTypeWorkflow StepType = \"workflow\"   // invoke another workflow\n)\n```\n\n**Known Config Keys** (defined in `/workspace/internal/domain/workflow.go:135-146`):\n- `prompt` — File path or direct string for agent steps (resolved via `file()` function)\n- `run` — Shell command for script steps\n- `max_attempts` — Max retry count (string, converted to int)\n- `timeout` — Execution timeout\n- `agent_command` — Override agent command (e.g., \"claude\")\n- `agent_args` — Override agent arguments\n- `results` — Result names (but stored separately, not in Config)\n- `feedback` — Enable feedback inclusion (\"true\"/\"false\")\n- `workflow_name` — Name of workflow to invoke (for workflow steps)\n- `prompt_step` — Step to use for workflow prompt\n- `container.*` — Container config (any key with prefix allowed)\n\n### How the Parser Sets Config Values\n\n**Parser flow** (`/workspace/internal/dsl/parser.go:139-198`):\n\n1. **Step parsing** (`parseStep()` lines 139-198):\n   - Parses step name and fields into `Config` map\n   - **Type inference** (lines 166-195): Looks at which of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name` is present\n   - Must have exactly one of these three keys\n\n2. **Field parsing** (`parseStepField()` lines 200-248):\n   - Handles regular fields: `key = value` → `Config[\"key\"] = value`\n   - Handles nested blocks: `container { image = \"...\" }` → `Config[\"container.image\"] = ...`\n   - Special case: `results = [...]` stores identifiers in `Step.Results`, NOT in `Config`\n   - String lists stored as comma-separated: `[\"a\", \"b\"]` → `\"a,b\"`\n\n3. **Value parsing** (`parseValue()` lines 298-342):\n   - Handles function calls: `file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")` → stored as string `file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")`\n   - Handles dotted paths: `step.code.output` → stored as literal string `\"step.code.output\"`\n   - Direct strings or identifiers stored as-is\n\n### File Path Storage\n\n**Key insight**: File paths are **not resolved during parsing**—they're stored in their raw form:\n- `prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")` → stored as `Config[\"prompt\"] = 'file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")'`\n- Resolution happens later in `prompt.resolveContent()` (`/workspace/internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go:321-333`)\n\nThe resolver extracts the path from the `file(\"...\")` syntax:\n```go\nfunc resolveContent(value string, workDir string) (string, error) {\n    // Check for file(\"path\") syntax from DSL parser\n    if strings.HasPrefix(value, `file(\"`) && strings.HasSuffix(value, `\")`) {\n        path := value[6 : len(value)-2]  // Extract path from file(\"...\")\n        data, err := os.ReadFile(filepath.Join(workDir, path))\n        if err != nil {\n            return \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"reading file %q: %w\", path, err)\n        }\n        return string(data), nil\n    }\n    return value, nil\n}\n```\n\n### Example Workflow\n\n`.cloche/develop.cloche` shows actual usage:\n```\nstep implement {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")    # Config[\"prompt\"] = 'file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")'\n    results = [success, fail]                         # Step.Results = [\"success\", \"fail\"]\n}\n\nstep test {\n    run = \"go test ./... 2>&1\"                        # Config[\"run\"] = \"go test ./... 2>&1\"\n    results = [success, fail]                         # Step.Results = [\"success\", \"fail\"]\n}\n\nstep fix {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/fix.md\")\n    max_attempts = \"2\"                                # Config[\"max_attempts\"] = \"2\"\n    results = [success, fail, give-up]\n}\n```\n\n### Runtime Usage\n\nWhen executing:\n1. **Agent steps** (`/workspace/internal/agent/runner.go:110-138`): Check for `step.Config[\"prompt\"]` or `step.Config[\"run\"]`\n2. **Max attempts** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go:70-78`): Read `Config[\"max_attempts\"]` as string, parse to int\n3. **Feedback** (`/workspace/internal/adapters/agents/prompt/prompt.go:300`): Check `step.Config[\"feedback\"] == \"true\"`\n4. **Agent command override** (`/workspace/internal/agent/runner.go:123-128`): Read and parse `step.Config[\"agent_command\"]` and `step.Config[\"agent_args\"]`\n\nAll config values remain strings throughout—conversion happens only where needed (e.g., parsing max_attempts to int, checking feedback equality)."}],"totalDurationMs":25540,"totalTokens":38376,"totalToolUseCount":11,"usage":{"input_tokens":5,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7788,"cache_read_input_tokens":29157,"output_tokens":1426,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":7788},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01784dHTb8txuEsBtCSMJKoC","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the issue. The `handleAPIStepContent` handler checks for `step.Config[\"prompt\"]`, `step.Config[\"command\"]`, and `step.Config[\"script\"]`. But from the DSL parser:\n\n1. Prompt values are stored as `file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")` (with the `file(\"...\")` wrapper), not as plain paths\n2. Script/command steps use `Config[\"run\"]`, not `Config[\"command\"]` or `Config[\"script\"]`\n\nSo the handler has two bugs:\n1. For agent steps: `step.Config[\"prompt\"]` contains `file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")` but the handler tries to use it directly as a file path via `os.ReadFile(filepath.Join(dir, prompt))` - it needs to strip the `file(\"...\")` wrapper first\n\n\n2. For script steps: the handler is looking for the wrong config keys - it should check `Config[\"run\"]` instead of `Config[\"command\"]` and `Config[\"script\"]`\n\nI need to fix both of these issues.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1834,"cache_read_input_tokens":37696,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1834},"output_tokens":13,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"287f3a27-118f-4f7e-b0f1-0e7789c0a986","uuid":"8be8a15c-5637-4b0d-84fb-0d191a79890a"}
